Module 5 Homework¶

In this assignment, we're going to tackle the most important aspect of time-series modeling: how to backtest our model!

Learning objectives:

  • Why do we need to backtest a time-series forecasting model
  • How to do pseudo-out-of-sample testing
  • How to do rolling pseudo-out-of-sample testing

We understand the importance of testing our models in general. If we didn't test our models, we wouldn't know if they're overfitting or underfitting, for example. A model that won't behave well out-of-sample (on observations it hasn't seen yet) is pretty much as useless to us as no model at all.

Testing a time-series model is more involved than testing most other machine learning models, and so we have dedicated an entire module to it.

1) Imports and setup¶

For continuity, we're going to use the same dataset as our prior time-series module. Let's read in the data, change the index to a datetime format, and plot the data at a monthly frequency.

import statsmodels.tsa.api as smt
import seaborn as sns

def acf_pacf_plots(data, lags=None):
    # create the structure for the plots
    layout = (1, 3)
    raw  = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (0, 0))
    acf  = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (0, 1))
    pacf = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (0, 2))
    
    # create the actual plots
    data.plot(ax=raw, figsize=(12, 6))
    smt.graphics.plot_acf(data, lags=lags, ax=acf)
    smt.graphics.plot_pacf(data, lags=lags, ax=pacf)
    sns.despine()
    plt.tight_layout()

3) In-sample prediction¶

When we use our model to predict for time stamps that we already have data for, we call that in-sample prediction. When we'd like to know what our model thinks will happen in the future, for time stamps where we don't have data, we call that out-of-sample forecasting.

Let's practice our in-sample prediction and plotting before we get to out-of-sample testing.

Now we'll want to get the in-sample predictions from the AR model we just built. Use .predict to do so.

In [116]:

in_sample = AR.predict(start=30,end=len(monthly_min_temp_df), dynamic=True)

Now that we have our in_sample prediction data, plot the predictions and the monthly actual data on the same chart.

4) Out-of-sample prediction¶

Let's do one true out-of-sample prediction. To do so, we'll again use .predict from statsmodels, but we'll want to start at the end of our actual data and go one year into the future.

To do so, set start to the length of our actual monthly data minus one (the minus one is so that our actual and prediction connect). Then set the end to be the length of our actual monthly data plus 12; this will predict out 12 time stamps or 12 months.

In [118]:
# TODO create out_of_sample data using .predict 

out_of_sample = AR.predict(start=len(monthly_min_temp_df)-1, end=len(monthly_min_temp_df)+12, dynamic=True)

5) Psuedo out-of-sample prediction, or train/test split for time-series¶

Above we did a real out-of-sample prediction by looking at 12 months into the future. But, in order to backtest our model, we need to do pseudo (or fake) out-of-sample prediction. This is how it will work:

  • Pretend as if we have less data than we actually do
  • Build a model on the smaller dataset that excludes the data we're pretending not to have
  • Compare the out-of-sample forecast built on the smaller dataset with the actual data for those timestamps

We can think of this as a train/test split for time series.

Create a pseudo out-of-sample dataset. Call the dataset we'll build our model on train and the part we'll hold out as the psuedo out-of-sample test.

To start, hold out the last 12 time steps (aka 12 months) of data.

6) Rolling out-of-sample testing¶

Doing a single out-of-sample train/test split is all well and good, but we need to do more. That's where rolling out-of-sample testing comes in. What we'll want to do now is the systematically hold out a large amount of data, run a model, then hold out slightly less data and repeat. Let's do it!

7) Write a loop to automate out-of-sample testing¶

Let's put it all together now! Write a for-loop to automate your pseudo out-of-sample testing. Start with the first 24 months of data in your training set, and in each step add another 12 months.

In [141]:
# TODO build a loop to automate pseudo out-of-sample testing

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.ar_model import AutoReg
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# store the RMSE from each run in a list, then plot that list as a line graph to see how it changes as you add more data

# Create an empty list to store RMSE values
rmse_list = []

# Define the initial training size and increment size
initial_train_size = 24  # months
increment_size = 12      # months

# Loop through the dataset
for start in range(initial_train_size, len(monthly_min_temp_df), increment_size):
    # Define training and testing sets
    train = monthly_min_temp_df['temp'][:start]
    test = monthly_min_temp_df['temp'][start:start + increment_size]
    
    # Fit the AR model
    model = AutoReg(train, lags=9)  # Adjust lag as needed
    model_fit = model.fit()
    
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model_fit.predict(start=len(train), end=len(train) + len(test) - 1)
    
    # Calculate RMSE
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test, predictions))
    rmse_list.append(rmse)

# Plotting RMSE values
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(initial_train_size, len(monthly_min_temp_df), increment_size), rmse_list, marker='o')
plt.title('RMSE vs. Training Size')
plt.xlabel('Training Size (Months)')
plt.ylabel('RMSE')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Check for understanding: Why do we have to start with 24 months of data? Why didn't we start with 12 months, or even fewer? Remember how an AR model works, particularly what the AR lag means! Compare this to the value we used for our AR lag in this particular model. Could we build a model with fewer datapoints than our lag? Try and see what statsmodels tells you!

# TODO write a few sentences to answer the above question¶

  • This is the message, ValueError: The model specification cannot be estimated. The model contains 10 regressors (1 trend, 0 seasonal, 9 lags) but after adjustment for hold_back and creation of the lags, there are only 3 data points available to estimate parameters.
  • It looks like it needs 10 values to fit the regressors, and only 3 data points are available to fit and estimate accuracy against.
  • Once we use 24 we have 14 points available to create estimations of our data against. Robustness is very important when running AI models, it's actually very impressive that we can run an ML model with such small sample, 24 datapoints.

8) How to use rolling pseudo out-of-sample testing in practice¶

Now that we've had some practice with rolling pseudo out-of-sample testing, let's take a moment to reflect on what it all means. Did the RMSE always go down as we added more data? Nope! Sometimes it went up! That's because our time-series, although it's stationary, doesn't always have the same exact statistical properties over every cut of the data. That is, each training set didn't look exactly the same, so some may have had spikes or dips that affected our forecast.

Also, remember that time-series forecasts are valid only for a few time stamps out from the end of our data! They will degrade as we go out too far.

In fact, take a moment to answer this question: what happens to a time-series forecast as it's extended far into the future? How can we answer this question? We can look at our early out-of-sample performance, for example when we built our model on only the first 24 months of data. Look at the model forecast vs. the actual over time. Do you notice something about the forecast? You should notice that, the longer we go out into the future, the more that the forecast becomes just the mean of the training set.

Do an experiment: run a forecast an absurd amount of time into the future, say 36 or 48 months. What do you notice?

In [143]:
# TODO run experiment where you forecast an absurd amount of time into the future, such as 3, 4 or even 10 years

train = monthly_min_temp_df[:24]

Do an experiment: run a forecast an absurd amount of time into the future, say 36 or 48 months. What do you notice?

  • The data just defaults to the mean, the volatility of the forecast decreases and we are not aloud to capture the trend or volatility.
  • This example makes it clear that ARIMA should only be used for near future forecasts .

In practice, we use the stability of pseudo out-of-sample testing to judge our model. That is, we saw above that our RMSE didn't always go down, even as we added more data. When we use this paradigm of testing, this is what we look for to judge if our model is indeed good:

  • A good model should (in general) have decreasing RMSE as we add more data
  • It's ok if the RMSE doesn't always decrease as we add data, but in general the trend should be down
  • The model should become more stable as we add more data to our training set: that is, it should fit to any spikes better as we add training data

This is not an exact science! Rather, we take the whole of our rolling psuedo out-of-sample testing into consideration when we're trying to judge whether our model is behaving well.

9) A word of warning about time-series forecasting in finance¶

Out-of-sample testing in time-series modeling is a complex issue. We saw one very popular approach, but there are several ways it can be amended. However, what we need to know when we use time-series modelig in the real world is that no amount of testing will lead to perfect models.

Especially in finance applications of time-series modeling, the past is not a perfect guide to the future. If it were possible, for example, to predict future prices well enough to beat the market, then everyone would do it. But of course that's not possible. So I'd like to leave you with this warning: even a successful backtest does not prove anything about cause/effect. A backtest is not an experiment of what might happen in the future, it is simple a single hypothetical of what happened in the past. Do not overly rely on a backtest!

So then why did we just spend all this time doing rolling backtests? Well, a backtest is not completely useless. A backtest, especially as we did here with a rolling sample, does give us some information about our model. It could tell us, for example, if our model is completely ill-fit.

A common use of backtests in finance is for scenario analysis. Scenario analysis is beyond the scope of our course as it involves multiplte time-series (instead of a single series used in ARIMA), but it's helpful to understand in theory. A scenario analysis involves seeing how our time series would react if certain input variables are changed. For example, if we're modeling the amount of deposits in checking accounts that a bank will have over time, we can change the unemployment rate in each scenario and check how the balances do. Scenario analysis in this way is often used by central banks to check the health of the banks they regulate.
